Part I - Reporting Carrier On-Time Performance¶

by Abdullah S. Othman¶

Introduction¶

This dataset is all about airline on-time performance. It tracks flights over multiple years, mainly focusing on the years after 2000, and gives us a detailed look at how airlines are performing when it comes to on-time arrivals, delays, cancellations, and other important metrics.

# Function to plot histograms
def plot_histogram(data, column, bins=50, color='blue', title='Distribution', xlabel='Value', ylabel='Frequency'):
    """
    Plots a histogram with a KDE.
    :param data: The dataframe containing the column.
    :param column: The column name to plot.
    :param bins: Number of bins for the histogram.
    :param color: Color of the histogram.
    :param title: Title of the plot.
    :param xlabel: Label for the X-axis.
    :param ylabel: Label for the Y-axis.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data[column], bins=bins, kde=True, color=color)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()


def plot_countplot(data, column, title='Bar Plot', xlabel='Category', ylabel='Count'):
    """
    Plots a bar plot for a given categorical column.
    :param data: The dataframe containing the column.
    :param column: The column name to plot.
    :param title: Title of the plot.
    :param xlabel: Label for the X-axis.
    :param ylabel: Label for the Y-axis.
    """
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.countplot(data=data, x=column, palette='Set2', order=data[column].value_counts().nlargest(10).index)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.show()

1. Distribution of Arrival Delays¶

  • Key Observations:
    • The histogram shows a right-skewed distribution. Most flights have small or no delays, with a significant concentration around 0 minutes.
    • There is a long tail of delays, where a small proportion of flights experience extremely long delays exceeding 500 minutes.
    • The peak at 0 minutes likely represents on-time flights, which dominate the dataset.
  • Insights:
    • The majority of flights arrive on time or with minor delays.
    • Extreme delays (outliers) could skew averages and warrant further investigation into their causes (e.g., carrier, weather, or airport factors).

3. Number of Flights from Each Origin Airport¶

  • Key Observations:
    • Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport (ATL) is the busiest origin airport, followed by Chicago O'Hare (ORD) and Dallas/Fort Worth (DFW).
    • The top 10 airports handle a disproportionately large share of flights in the dataset.
    • Airports like LAX (Los Angeles), DEN (Denver), and PHX (Phoenix) also rank among the busiest.
  • Insights:
    • The busiest airports are likely major hubs and could be more prone to delays due to congestion.
    • Comparing delays at these high-traffic airports with smaller airports could reveal interesting patterns.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The variable of primary interest, arrival delays, exhibits a right-skewed distribution, with the majority of flights having small or no delays and a smaller proportion of flights experiencing significant delays exceeding 500 minutes. This skewness is typical for delay data, as most flights tend to run on schedule or with minor delays, while extreme delays are relatively rare.

Despite the skew, no transformations were applied to the data. The reason for this decision is that the skewness does not hinder the interpretability or utility of the data for this analysis. The raw distribution effectively conveys the key patterns and aligns with the real-world characteristics of flight delays, making transformation unnecessary for the current exploratory goals.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Among the features investigated:

  • Arrival Delays: The distribution is heavily right-skewed, which is expected given the nature of delay data. While there are extreme outliers in the form of significant delays, these represent real events and are important to the analysis. No adjustments were made to this data, as the skewness and outliers provide meaningful insights into delay patterns.
  • Flight Distances: The distribution is left-skewed, with the majority of flights covering short to medium distances. This is consistent with the real-world dominance of short-haul flights and does not require any adjustments.
  • Origin Airports: The count plot shows that a small number of airports dominate the dataset in terms of flight volume. This pattern aligns with the hub-and-spoke model of air travel, where a few major hubs handle the majority of flights. No adjustments were needed for this categorical feature.

Overall, no operations were performed to tidy, adjust, or transform the data. The observed distributions reflect real-world behaviors and do not interfere with the goals of this exploratory analysis.

Bivariate Exploration¶

Is there a relationship between departure delay and arrival delay? Do longer departure delays result in longer arrival delays?

In [33]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(data=Flights_df, x='DepDelay', y='ArrDelay', alpha=0.3)
plt.title('Relationship Between Departure Delay and Arrival Delay')
plt.xlabel('Departure Delay (minutes)')
plt.ylabel('Arrival Delay (minutes)')
plt.axhline(0, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)  # Zero arrival delay line
plt.axvline(0, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)  # Zero departure delay line
plt.show()

1. Scatter Plot: Relationship Between Departure Delay and Arrival Delay¶

  • Key Observations:

    • There is a strong positive correlation between departure delay and arrival delay. Flights with longer departure delays tend to have proportionally longer arrival delays.
    • The points are densely clustered near the origin (indicating flights with minimal delays) but show a clear upward trend as departure delay increases.
    • Some outliers exhibit extreme delays (e.g., beyond 1000 minutes for arrival or departure delays), which represent unusual events.

  • Insights:

    • Departure delays are a significant predictor of arrival delays, meaning on-time departures are crucial for maintaining schedule integrity.

3. Heatmap: Correlation Between Numerical Variables¶

    • Distance has very little correlation with delays (both arrival and departure), suggesting that flight length does not significantly influence delay durations.

  • Insights:

    • The high correlation between departure and arrival delays reinforces the importance of timely departures in avoiding arrival delays.
    • The minimal relationship between distance and delays indicates that delays are likely influenced by operational or environmental factors rather than the length of the flight.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The feature of interest, arrival delay, showed a strong positive correlation with departure delay. This relationship indicates that longer departure delays often lead to proportionally longer arrival delays. Flights with minimal departure delays generally had minimal arrival delays, whereas significant departure delays led to extreme arrival delays in some cases.

Additionally, arrival delay exhibited variability across different carriers. While most carriers showed median arrival delays close to zero, some carriers had larger variability in delay durations, suggesting operational differences or route-specific challenges. Outliers in arrival delays were present for some carriers, which may be attributed to specific flights or circumstances.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Yes, a few interesting relationships were observed between other features:

  • Departure Delay and Distance: There was no strong correlation between the distance of a flight and its departure delay, indicating that flight length does not significantly impact delay durations.
  • Distance and Arrival Delay: Similarly, flight distance showed little to no relationship with arrival delay, suggesting that delays are more influenced by operational or environmental factors rather than flight length.
  • Carriers and Variability: The distribution of delays across carriers revealed that while most carriers perform similarly, certain carriers showed higher variability or more frequent extreme delays, which could point to specific inefficiencies or external influences.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Do different carriers show distinct patterns in the relationship between departure and arrival delays?

In [38]:
g = sns.FacetGrid(Flights_df, col="Reporting_Airline", col_wrap=4, height=4, aspect=1.2)
g.map(sns.scatterplot, "DepDelay", "ArrDelay", alpha=0.3)
g.set_axis_labels("Departure Delay (minutes)", "Arrival Delay (minutes)")
g.set_titles("{col_name} Carrier")
g.fig.suptitle("Arrival vs Departure Delay by Carrier", y=1.05)
plt.show()

Facet Plot: Arrival Delay vs Departure Delay by Carrier¶

  • Key Observations:

    • Strong Positive Correlation Across Carriers:

      • All carriers exhibit a strong positive linear relationship between departure delay and arrival delay, indicating that departure delays consistently propagate to arrival delays regardless of the carrier.

    • Clusters Around Zero Delays:

      • Most data points are concentrated near the origin (zero delays), showing that the majority of flights depart and arrive on time or with minimal delays.

    • Variability in Outliers:

      • Some carriers, such as DL, AA, EV, and OO, show a wider spread of extreme delays, suggesting they experience more frequent or severe delays.
      • Carriers like DH and VX have fewer visible outliers, which may indicate more consistent performance and fewer operational disruptions.

    • Negative Delays:

      • Negative values for both departure delay and arrival delay represent early departures and arrivals. These are consistent across carriers and are clustered around small negative values.

    • Carrier-Specific Patterns:

      • Carriers with higher densities of extreme delays may face specific operational challenges or routes prone to disruptions.
      • Smaller carriers or those with limited data (e.g., KH and TZ) show less variability, which could reflect fewer flights in the dataset.

  • Insights:

    • Propagation of Delays:

      • Departure delays are a primary driver of arrival delays across all carriers. Addressing departure delays could significantly reduce arrival delays.

    • Operational Consistency:

      • Carriers with fewer outliers, such as DH and VX, demonstrate more consistent operational performance. This suggests better delay management or fewer disruptions.

    • Actionable Insights for Outliers:

      • Carriers with more frequent extreme delays (e.g., DL, AA, and OO) may need targeted investigations to identify and address root causes, such as specific routes or external factors like weather.

  • Insights:

    • Predictability of Delays:

      • Departure delay remains a key determinant of arrival delay, regardless of flight distance or carrier. This reinforces the importance of addressing operational delays at departure.

    • Consistency Across Carriers:

      • The overlapping data points for different carriers suggest consistent delay patterns across the industry, with no single carrier standing out as significantly better or worse in this context.

    • Minimal Influence of Distance:

      • The size of the bubbles (representing flight distance) does not significantly impact the observed delays, indicating that delays are more likely caused by operational or environmental factors than the flight's length.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The feature of interest, arrival delay, was strongly influenced by departure delay across all visualizations. This relationship consistently emerged in both bivariate and multivariate analyses. The facet plot and scatterplot highlighted a clear linear correlation between the two variables, suggesting that minimizing departure delays is critical for reducing arrival delays.

Additionally, carrier played a role in understanding delay variability. While most carriers followed similar trends, the facet plot revealed that some carriers had larger distributions of delays, which might require operational improvements. The multivariate scatterplot further emphasized that flight distance does not significantly affect delays, allowing us to focus more on operational and carrier-specific factors when addressing delays.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Yes, a few interesting interactions were observed:

  1. Consistency Across Carriers:

    • Despite operational differences, the delay trends across carriers were surprisingly similar. The strong positive correlation between departure and arrival delays was consistent for all carriers, with minor variations in delay spread.

  2. Minimal Impact of Flight Distance:

    • It was surprising that flight distance had little to no impact on delays. Larger flight distances did not result in longer delays, suggesting that delays are driven more by operational or environmental factors than by the flight's length.

  3. Outliers Across Carriers:

    • Some carriers, such as DL, AA, and OO, had more frequent extreme delays, while others, such as DH and VX, had fewer outliers. This variability was unexpected and warrants further investigation into what factors contribute to these extremes, such as specific routes or external influences.

Conclusions¶

Summary of Main Findings¶

  1. Univariate Exploration:

    • Arrival Delays: Most flights had minimal delays, with a few significant outliers causing extreme delays.
    • Flight Distance: Short- and medium-haul flights dominated the dataset, with fewer long-haul flights.
    • Origin Airports: Major hubs like ATL and ORD had the highest flight volumes.

  2. Bivariate Exploration:

    • Arrival vs. Departure Delays: Strong positive correlation, confirming that departure delays are the primary driver of arrival delays.
    • Carrier Variability: Most carriers showed consistent delay trends, but some exhibited higher variability and more outliers.
    • Correlation: Flight distance showed no significant correlation with delays.

  3. Multivariate Exploration:

    • Consistency Across Carriers: Delay patterns were similar across carriers, with departure delays strongly influencing arrival delays.
    • Minimal Impact of Distance: Flight distance had little effect on delay severity, highlighting the role of operational factors.

Key Takeaways¶

  • Addressing departure delays is critical for reducing arrival delays.
  • Flight distance does not significantly influence delays, shifting the focus to operational and environmental factors.
  • Some carriers manage delays better, suggesting opportunities for industry-wide improvements.

The analysis provided clear insights into delay patterns and identified key areas for operational improvement.
